---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import VectorSpaceScene from "../../../components/VectorSpaceScene3D.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleScenario from "../../../components/module/ModuleScenario.astro";
import ModuleFlowDiagram from "../../../components/module/ModuleFlowDiagram.astro";
import ModelMismatchDemo from "../../../components/module/demos/ModelMismatchDemo.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleRecap from "../../../components/module/ModuleRecap.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "20-embeddings";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="20 · Embeddings & vector store">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        Module 15 gave you chunks — small enough to be meaningful, but still just text. This module turns each
        chunk into a vector, and stores those vectors in an index built for one operation: "find me the K vectors
        closest to this one." That single operation is what makes retrieval possible at all.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <ModuleScenario moduleId={moduleId} />

    <ModuleFlowDiagram moduleId={moduleId} />

    <VectorSpaceScene />

    <h2>Picking an embedding model</h2>
    <p>
      Embedding models differ in dimensionality, language coverage, and what kind of similarity they were trained to
      capture. The practical rule: use the same model to embed your chunks and your queries — mixing models breaks
      the geometry the whole index depends on — and prefer a model your cloud's retrieval service integrates with
      natively, since that keeps the embed → store → search path in one system instead of three.
    </p>

    <ModelMismatchDemo />

    <h2>What the vector index actually stores</h2>
    <p>
      Beyond the vector itself, every entry needs enough metadata to be useful once retrieved: the source
      document, the chunk's original text, its position, and anything Module 65 (security) will later need for
      access control. An index with vectors but no metadata can find a match — it just can't tell you what it
      found or whether the requesting user is allowed to see it.
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Embedding queries with a different model than the one used for chunks — similarity breaks silently, not loudly.</li>
      <li>Storing vectors with no metadata — you can retrieve a match but not explain or filter it.</li>
      <li>Re-embedding the entire index by hand after a chunking change — plan for incremental re-embedding from day one (Module 11: Orchestration).</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleRecap moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
